title: Measurement of the cross sections for the reactions Cr-52(n,2n)Cr-51, Zn-66(n,2n)Zn-65, Y-89(n,2n)Y-88 and Zr-96(n,2n)Zr-95 from 13.5 to 14.8 MeV.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Annals of Nuclear Energy, Vol.16, Issue.12, p.623 (1989)
Rept: IAEA Nucl.Data Section report to the I.N.D.C., No.232, p.17 (1990)

x4freetext: Similar, same data
Measurement of the cross sections for the reactions
and Zr-96(n,2n)Zr-95 from 13.5 to 14.8 MeV.
Neutrons were produced by bombarding a 0.5 mm
thick Al-backed Ti-T target with a 190 +- 10 keV
deuteron beam. Neutron energy was selected by the
angular position of the sample with respect to the
deuteron beam axis. The neutron-energy scale was
verified by measuring the ratios of the Zr-89 to
Nb-92-m specific activities induced in sandwiched Zr
and Nb foils at 12.5 and 97.5 degrees and comparing
them to expected ones based on existing cross section
data.
Yttrium-oxide powder samples and high-purity metallic
samples of natural Cr,Zn and Zr.
For the yttrium-oxide samples, sandwiched
between two Nb foils, the mean of the fluences at both
monitor foils was taken. In all other cases the fluence
at the sample position was calculated from the fluence
at the monitor foil position using a 1/r**2 dependence
and accounting for neutron absorption in the sample
and monitor foil.
Neutron fluence.
Nb foils with the same shape as the samples were placed
back-to-back behind each sample. The yttrium-oxide
samples were sandwiched between two fluence monitor
foils.

x4freetext: Activation enhancement due to elastic neutron scat-
tering in the sample and monitor foils and due to
inscattering by neighbouring material was estimated.
In all cases where applicable, the corrections for
this and for relating the measured cross sections to
the average neutron energy were negligible.
Nonnegligible uncertainties involve
uncertainties in:
* counting statistics,
* relative gamma counts-to-activity convers. factors,
* mass and purity of samples,
* isotopic abundance,
* survival factor of Nb-92-m,
* detector efficiencies,
* average neutron energies,
* monitor reference cross section and
* irradiation geometry.
Total uncertainties in cross sections were obtained
by adding the uncertainty components (standard
deviations) in quadrature.
Detailed information on the size of all sources of
uncertainties is given in Tables 3 and 4 of the
reference.
Data are taken from Table 2 of Ann.Nucl.Energy,

x4freetext: For results of analysis at IRK see subentry 30972007
When measuring the Zr-95 activity produced in the
nat. Zr(n,x) reaction,
one measures the sum of the following cross sections:
a) the Zr-96(n,2n) reaction, providing by far
the main contribution;
b) the Zr-96 (n,d)+(n,np)+(n,pn) Y-95 reaction,
since Y-95 decays to Zr-95 via beta- emission;
c) the Zr-94(n,g)Zr-95 reaction, weighted by a
factor 6.207, which is the ratio of the isotopic
abundances of Zr-94 to Zr-96 in natural Zr.

x4freetext: For results of analysis at KFI see subentry 30972003
With the NaI(Tl) both the Zr-95 and Nb-95 activities
were counted since a small fraction of the Zr-95
(1.11%) decays feed the 235.7 keV Nb-95-m state which
itself decays mainly to the groundstate of Nb-95. From
the irradiation time, production rate for Zr-95 and
both decay constants the specific Zr-95 activity at the
end of the irradiation was evaluated.
When measuring the sum of the Zr-95 and Nb-95 activi-
ties produced in the nat. Zr(n,x) reaction, one measu-
res the sum of the following cross sections:
a) the Zr-96(n,2n) reaction, providing by far
the main contribution;
b) the Zr-96 (n,d)+(n,np)+(n,pn) Y-95 reaction,
since Y-95 decays to Zr-95 via beta- emission;
c) the Zr-94(n,g)Zr-95 reaction, weighted by a
factor 6.207, which is the ratio of the isotopic
abundances of Zr-94 to Zr-96 in natural Zr.
With the intrinsic Germanium detector
the relative activities of the Zr-95 samples and their
monitor foils were determined. For normalization
purposes absolute measurements were performed on the
sample with the highest activity, employing a NaI(Ti)
well-type detector.
